# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ultralight-ui
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics are mainly used in applications that were originally developed upon traditional printing and drawing technologies, such as typography, cartography, technical drawing, advertising, etc.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] In many domains, such as desktop publishing, engineering, and business, a description of a document based on 2D computer graphics techniques can be much smaller than the corresponding digital image—often by a factor of 1/1000 or more.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] This representation is also more flexible since it can be rendered at different resolutions to suit different output devices.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, documents and illustrations are often stored or transmitted as 2D graphic files.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics started in the 1950s, based on vector graphics devices.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] These were largely supplanted by raster-based devices in the following decades.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] The PostScript language and the X Window System protocol were landmark developments in the field.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics models may combine geometric models (also called vector graphics), digital images (also called raster graphics), text to be typeset (defined by content, font style and size, color, position, and orientation), mathematical functions and equations, and more.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] These components can be modified and manipulated by two-dimensional geometric transformations such as translation, rotation, and scaling.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] In object-oriented graphics, the image is described indirectly by an object endowed with a self-rendering method—a procedure that assigns colors to the image pixels by an arbitrary algorithm.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Complex models can be built by combining simpler objects, in the paradigms of object-oriented programming.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] In Euclidean geometry, a *translation (geometry)* moves every point a constant distance in a specified direction.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can be described as a rigid motion: other rigid motions include rotations and reflections.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can also be interpreted as the addition of a constant vector to every point, or as shifting the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] If *T* is a translation, then the image of a subset *A* under the function *T* is the **translation** of *A* by *T*.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] The translation of *A* by *T***v** is often written *A* + **v**.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] In a Euclidean space, any translation is an isometry.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all translations forms the translation group *T*, which is isomorphic to the space itself, and a normal subgroup of Euclidean group *E*(*n* ).
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Since a translation is an affine transformation but not a linear transformation, homogeneous coordinates are normally used to represent the translation operator by a matrix and thus to make it linear.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Because addition of vectors is commutative, multiplication of translation matrices is therefore also commutative (unlike multiplication of arbitrary matrices).
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] In linear algebra, a *rotation matrix* is a matrix that is used to perform a rotation in Euclidean space.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] rotates points in the *xy*-Cartesian plane counterclockwise through an angle *θ* about the origin of the Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] To perform the rotation using a rotation matrix *R*, the position of each point must be represented by a column vector **v**, containing the coordinates of the point.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] A rotated vector is obtained by using the matrix multiplication *R***v**.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Since matrix multiplication has no effect on the zero vector (i.e., on the coordinates of the origin), rotation matrices can only be used to describe rotations about the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices provide a simple algebraic description of such rotations, and are used extensively for computations in geometry, physics, and computer graphics.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] In 2-dimensional space, a rotation can be simply described by an angle *θ* of rotation, but it can be also represented by the 4 entries of a rotation matrix with 2 rows and 2 columns.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] In 3-dimensional space, every rotation can be interpreted as a rotation by a given angle about a single fixed axis of rotation (see Euler's rotation theorem), and hence it can be simply described by an angle and a vector with 3 entries.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] However, it can also be represented by the 9 entries of a rotation matrix with 3 rows and 3 columns.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] The notion of rotation is not commonly used in dimensions higher than 3; there is a notion of a *rotational displacement*, which can be represented by a matrix, but no associated single axis or angle.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices are square matrices, with real entries.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all such matrices of size *n* forms a group, known as the special orthogonal group SO(*n*).
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] A convenient way to create a complex image is to start with a blank "canvas" raster map (an array of pixels, also known as a bitmap) filled with some uniform background color and then "draw", "paint" or "paste" simple patches of color onto it, in an appropriate order.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] In particular the canvas may be the frame buffer for a computer display.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Text, shapes and lines are rendered with a client-specified color.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Many libraries and cards provide color gradients, which are handy for the generation of smoothly-varying backgrounds, shadow effects, etc.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] The pixel colors can also be taken from a texture, e.g. a digital image (thus emulating rub-on screentones and the fabled *checker paint* which used to be available only in cartoons).
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Painting a pixel with a given color usually replaces its previous color.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] However, many systems support painting with transparent and translucent colors, which only modify the previous pixel values.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] The two colors may also be combined in more complex ways, e.g. by computing their bitwise exclusive or.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] This technique is known as *inverting color* or *color inversion*, and is often used in graphical user interfaces for highlighting, rubber-band drawing, and other volatile painting—since re-painting the same shapes with the same color will restore the original pixel values.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] The models used in 2D computer graphics usually do not provide for three-dimensional shapes, or three-dimensional optical phenomena such as lighting, shadows, reflection, refraction, etc.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] However, they usually can model multiple *layers* (conceptually of ink, paper, or film; opaque, translucent, or transparent—stacked in a specific order.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] The ordering is usually defined by a single number (the layer's *depth*, or distance from the viewer).
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are sometimes called "21⁄2-D computer graphics".
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] They make it possible to mimic traditional drafting and printing techniques based on film and paper, such as cutting and pasting; and allow the user to edit any layer without affecting the others.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, they are used in most graphics editors.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models also allow better spatial anti-aliasing of complex drawings and provide a sound model for certain techniques such as *mitered joints* and the even–odd rule.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are also used to allow the user to suppress unwanted information when viewing or printing a document, e.g. roads or railways from a map, certain process layers from an integrated circuit diagram, or hand annotations from a business letter.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] In a layer-based model, the target image is produced by "painting" or "pasting" each layer, in order of decreasing depth, on the virtual canvas.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Conceptually, each layer is first rendered on its own, yielding a digital image with the desired resolution which is then painted over the canvas, pixel by pixel.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Fully transparent parts of a layer need not be rendered, of course.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] The rendering and painting may be done in parallel, i.e., each layer pixel may be painted on the canvas as soon as it is produced by the rendering procedure.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Layers that consist of complex geometric objects (such as text or polylines) may be broken down into simpler elements (characters or line segments, respectively), which are then painted as separate layers, in some order.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] However, this solution may create undesirable aliasing artifacts wherever two elements overlap the same pixel.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] See also Portable Document Format#Layers.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Modern computer graphics card displays almost overwhelmingly use raster techniques, dividing the screen into a rectangular grid of pixels, due to the relatively low cost of raster-based video hardware as compared with vector graphic hardware.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Most graphic hardware has internal support for blitting operations or sprite drawing.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] A co-processor dedicated to blitting is known as a *Blitter chip*.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Many graphical user interfaces (GUIs), including macOS, Microsoft Windows, or the X Window System, are primarily based on 2D graphical concepts.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Such software provides a visual environment for interacting with the computer, and commonly includes some form of window manager to aid the user in conceptually distinguishing between different applications.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] The user interface within individual software applications is typically 2D in nature as well, due in part to the fact that most common input devices, such as the mouse, are constrained to two dimensions of movement.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics are very important in the control peripherals such as printers, plotters, sheet cutting machines, etc.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] They were also used in most early video games; and are still used for card and board games such as solitaire, chess, mahjongg, etc.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics editors or *drawing programs* are application-level software for the creation of images, diagrams and illustrations by direct manipulation (through the mouse, graphics tablet, or similar device) of 2D computer graphics primitives.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally provide geometric primitives as well as digital images; and some even support procedural models.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] The illustration is usually represented internally as a layered model, often with a hierarchical structure to make editing more convenient.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally output graphics files where the layers and primitives are separately preserved in their original form.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] MacDraw, introduced in 1984 with the Macintosh line of computers, was an early example of this class; recent examples are the commercial products Adobe Illustrator and CorelDRAW, and the free editors such as xfig or Inkscape.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] There are also many 2D graphics editors specialized for certain types of drawings such as electrical, electronic and VLSI diagrams, topographic maps, computer fonts, etc.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Image editors are specialized for the manipulation of digital images, mainly by means of free-hand drawing/painting and signal processing operations.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] They typically use a direct-painting paradigm, where the user controls virtual pens, brushes, and other free-hand artistic instruments to apply paint to a virtual canvas.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Some image editors support a multiple-layer model; however, in order to support signal-processing operations like blurring each layer is normally represented as a digital image.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Therefore, any geometric primitives that are provided by the editor are immediately converted to pixels and painted onto the canvas.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] The name *raster graphics editor* is sometimes used to contrast this approach to that of general editors which also handle *vector graphics*.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] One of the first popular image editors was Apple's MacPaint, companion to MacDraw.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Modern examples are the free GIMP editor, and the commercial products Photoshop and Paint Shop Pro.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] This class too includes many specialized editors—for medicine, remote sensing, digital photography, etc.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] With the resurgence of 2D animation, free and proprietary software packages have become widely available for amateurs and professional animators.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] With software like RETAS UbiArt Framework and Adobe After Effects, coloring and compositing can be done in less time.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Various approaches have been developed to aid and speed up the process of digital 2D animation.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] For example, by generating vector artwork in a tool like Adobe Flash an artist may employ software-driven automatic coloring and in-betweening.
[src:ultralight-ui/2d-computer-graphics] Programs like Blender or Adobe Substance allow the user to do either 3D animation, 2D animation or combine both in its software allowing experimentation with multiple forms of animation.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] GPUs are also increasingly being used for artificial intelligence (AI) processing due to linear algebra acceleration, which is also used extensively in graphics processing.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] This contrasts with earlier graphics controllers known as video display controllers which had no internal calculation capabilities, or blitters, which performed only basic memory movement operations.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The modern GPU emerged during the 1990s, adding the ability to perform operations like drawing lines and text without CPU help, and later adding 3D functionality.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Graphics functions are generally independent and this lends these tasks to being implemented on separate calculation engines.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Modern GPUs include hundreds, or thousands, of calculation units.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] This made them useful for non-graphic calculations involving embarrassingly parallel problems due to their parallel structure.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The ability of GPUs to rapidly perform vast numbers of calculations has led to their adoption in diverse fields including artificial intelligence (AI) where they excel at handling data-intensive and computationally demanding tasks.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Other non-graphical uses include the training of neural networks and cryptocurrency mining.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Many companies have produced GPUs under a number of brand names.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In 2009, Intel, Nvidia, and AMD/ATI were the market share leaders, with 49.4%, 27.8%, and 20.6% market share respectively.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In addition, Matrox while originally producing custom solutions, now customizes GPUs from Intel and AMD for workstation usage.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Chinese companies such as Jingjia Micro have also produced GPUs for the domestic market although in terms of worldwide sales, they lag behind market leaders.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Several factors of GPU construction affect the performance of the card for real-time rendering, such as the size of the connector pathways in the semiconductor device fabrication, the clock signal frequency, and the number and size of various on-chip memory caches.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] GPU performance is typically measured in floating point operations per second (FLOPS); Modern GPUs typically deliver performance measured in teraflops (TFLOPS).
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] This is an estimated performance measure, and should not be treated as fact, as other factors can affect actual performance.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Modern GPUs also include dedicated hardware blocks for ray tracing, video encoding, and AI acceleration.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In personal computers, there are two main forms of GPUs: dedicated graphics (also called discrete graphics) and integrated graphics (also called shared graphics solutions, integrated graphics processors (IGP), or unified memory architecture (UMA).
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Technologies such as Scalable Link Interface (SLI), NVLink, and CrossFire allow multiple GPUs to draw images simultaneously for a single screen, increasing the processing power available for graphics.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] These technologies, however, are increasingly uncommon; most games do not fully use multiple GPUs, as most users cannot afford them.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Because GPU computations are memory-intensive, integrated processing may compete with the CPU for relatively slow system RAM, as it has minimal or no dedicated video memory.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] IGPUs use system memory with bandwidth up to a current maximum of 128 gigabytes per second, whereas a discrete graphics card may have a bandwidth of more than 1000 gigabytes per second between its video random access memory (VRAM) and GPU core.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] This memory bus bandwidth can limit the performance of the IGPU, though multi-channel memory can mitigate this deficiency.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] On systems with "Unified Memory Architecture" (UMA), including modern AMD processors with integrated graphics, modern Intel processors with integrated graphics, Apple processors, and modern consoles, the CPU cores and the GPU block share the same pool of RAM and memory address space.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] It is common to use a general purpose graphics processing unit (GPGPU) as a modified form of stream processor or a vector processor, running compute kernels.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] This turns the massive computational power of a modern graphics accelerator's shader pipeline into general-purpose computing power.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In certain applications requiring massive vector operations, this can yield several orders of magnitude higher performance than a conventional CPU.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The two largest discrete GPU designers, AMD and Nvidia, are pursuing this approach with an array of applications.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia and AMD collaborated with Stanford University to create a GPU-based client for the Folding@home distributed computing project for protein folding calculations.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In certain circumstances, the GPU calculates forty times faster than the CPUs traditionally used by such applications.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] GPU-based high performance computers play a significant role in large-scale modelling.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Three of the ten most powerful supercomputers in the world take advantage of GPU acceleration.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Since 2005 there has been interest in using the performance offered by GPUs for evolutionary computation in general, and for accelerating the fitness evaluation in genetic programming in particular.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Most approaches compile linear or tree programs on the host PC and transfer the executable to the GPU to be run.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Typically a performance advantage is only obtained by running the single active program simultaneously on many example problems in parallel, using the GPU's single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) architecture.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Substantial acceleration can also be obtained by not compiling the programs, and instead transferring them to the GPU, to be interpreted there.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] A GPU can be attached to some external bus of a notebook.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] PCI Express is the only bus used for this purpose.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The port may be, for example, an ExpressCard or mPCIe port (PCIe ×1, up to 5 or 2.5 gigabits per second respectively), a Thunderbolt 1, 2, or 3 port (PCIe ×4, up to 10, 20, or 40 gigabits per second respectively), a USB4 port with Thunderbolt compatibility, or an OCuLink port.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Those ports are only available on certain notebook systems. eGPU enclosures include their own power supply (PSU), because powerful GPUs can consume hundreds of watts.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Dedicated 3D graphics hardware dates back to graphic terminals such as the Adage AGT-30 from 1967 with analog matrix processors.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In 1969 Evans & Sutherland (E&S) introduced the Line Drawing System-1 (LDS-1), which was the first all-digital system to provide matrix multiplication.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1969, the low-cost graphics terminal IMLAC PDS-1 was introduced.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] It later saw use as an early 3D gaming machine with the likes of Maze War.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In the 1970s, the term "GPU" originally stood for graphics processor unit and described a programmable processing unit working independently from the CPU that was responsible for graphics manipulation and output.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In professional hardware, in 1972 PLATO IV system becomes operational at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Between around 1973 and 1978, several networked multiplayer wireframe 3D games are implemented and popularized by users of the system.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1972, the E&S Continuous Tone 1 (CT1) "Watkins box" system (consisting of an E&S LDS-2 and Shaded Picture System) is delivered to Case Western Reserve University.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] It offered the first real-time Gouraud shading.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In 1975, a joint effort between Evans & Sutherland Computer Corporation and the University of Utah's computer graphics department results in the first ever MOSFET video framebuffer, capable of color and smooth shading.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] E&S Continuous Tone 3 (CT3) system was delivered in 1977 to Lufthansa for pilot training using computer simulation.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] It was the first graphics system capable of real-time texture mapping.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Ikonas made graphics systems with 8- and 24-bit graphics and 3D acceleration in the late 70s.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Arcade system boards have used specialized 2D graphics circuits since the 1970s.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In early video game hardware, RAM for frame buffers was expensive, so video chips composited data together as the display was being scanned out on the monitor.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] A specialized barrel shifter circuit helped the CPU animate the framebuffer graphics for various 1970s arcade video games from Midway and Taito, such as *Gun Fight* (1975), *Sea Wolf* (1976), and *Space Invaders* (1978).
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The Namco Galaxian arcade system in 1979 used specialized graphics hardware that supported RGB color, multi-colored sprites, and tilemap backgrounds.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The Galaxian hardware was widely used during the golden age of arcade video games, by game companies such as Namco, Centuri, Gremlin, Irem, Konami, Midway, Nichibutsu, Sega, and Taito.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The Atari 2600 in 1977 used a video shifter called the Television Interface Adaptor.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Atari 8-bit computers (1979) had ANTIC, a video processor which interpreted instructions describing a "display list"—the way the scan lines map to specific bitmapped or character modes and where the memory is stored (so there did not need to be a contiguous frame buffer).
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] 6502 machine code subroutines could be triggered on scan lines by setting a bit on a display list instruction.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] ANTIC also supported smooth vertical and horizontal scrolling independent of the CPU.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In the 1980s significant advancements were made in professional 3D graphics hardware.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Perhaps most impactful was the 1981 development of the Geometry Engine, a VLSI vector processor ASIC designed by Jim Clark and Marc Hannah at Stanford University.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] This processor is the forerunner of modern tensor cores and other similar processors marketed for graphics and AI.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The Geometry Engine went on to be used in Silicon Graphics workstations for many years.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Silicon Graphics's first product, shipped in November 1983, was the IRIS 1000, a terminal with hardware-accelerated 3D graphics based on the Geometry Engine.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The Geometry Engine was capable of approximately 6 million operations per second.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The 1981 NEC μPD7220 was the first implementation of a personal computer graphics display processor as a single large-scale integration (LSI) integrated circuit chip.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] This enabled the design of low-cost, high-performance video graphics cards such as those from Number Nine Visual Technology.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] It became the best-known GPU until the mid-1980s.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] It was the first fully integrated VLSI (very large-scale integration) metal–oxide–semiconductor (NMOS) graphics display processor for PCs, supported up to 1024×1024 resolution, and laid the foundations for the PC graphics market.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] It was used in a number of graphics cards and was licensed for clones such as the Intel 82720, the first of Intel's graphics processing units.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The Williams Electronics arcade games *Robotron: 2084*, *Joust*, *Sinistar*, and *Bubbles*, all released in 1982, contain custom blitter chips for operating on 16-color bitmaps.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In 1984, Hitachi released the ARTC HD63484, the first major CMOS graphics processor for personal computers.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The ARTC could display up to 4K resolution when in monochrome mode.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] It was used in a number of graphics cards and terminals during the late 1980s.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In 1985, the Amiga was released with a custom graphics chip called Agnus including a blitter for bitmap manipulation, line drawing, and area fill.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] It also included a coprocessor with its own simple instruction set, that was capable of manipulating graphics hardware registers in sync with the video beam (e.g. for per-scanline palette switches, sprite multiplexing, and hardware windowing), or driving the blitter.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1985, IBM released the Professional Graphics Controller, designed by later to be Nvidia co-founder Curtis Priem, which was a rudimentary 3D card with 640 × 480 256-color graphics which used a dedicated CPU to draw graphics independently of the main system.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] It was used as the basis of cards by a number of makers (including Matrox) and its analog RGB signaling led directly to the VGA video standard.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Priem later in the 80s worked on the influential Sun Microsystems GX (also known as cgsix) accelerated 2D graphics card.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In 1986, Texas Instruments released the TMS34010, the first fully programmable graphics processor.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] It could run general-purpose code but also had a graphics-oriented instruction set.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] During 1990–1992, this chip became the basis of the Texas Instruments Graphics Architecture ("TIGA") Windows accelerator cards.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Following in 1987, the IBM 8514 graphics system was released.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] It was one of the first video cards for IBM PC compatibles that implemented fixed-function 2D primitives in electronic hardware.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Sharp's X68000, released in 1987, used a custom graphics chipset with a 65,536 color palette and hardware support for sprites, scrolling, and multiple playfields.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] It served as a development machine for Capcom's CP System arcade board.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Fujitsu's FM Towns computer, released in 1989, had support for a 16,777,216 color palette.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] For context, IBM also introduced its Video Graphics Array (VGA) display system in 1987, with a maximum resolution of 640 × 480 pixels.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Unlike 8514/A, VGA had no hardware acceleration features.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In November 1988, NEC Home Electronics announced its creation of the Video Electronics Standards Association (VESA) to develop and promote a Super VGA (SVGA) computer display standard as a successor to VGA.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Super VGA enabled graphics display resolutions up to 800 × 600 pixels, a 56% increase.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In 1988 SGI sold IRIS workstation graphics with 10-12 Geometry Engines and introduced the IrisVision add-in board for IBM MicroChannel bus (RS/6000) based on the Geometry Engine as well.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In 1988 as well, the first dedicated polygonal 3D graphics boards in arcade machines were introduced with the Namco System 21 and Taito Air System.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The 1990s again saw considerable advancements in professional workstation 3D graphics hardware from Sun Microsystems, SGI, and others.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The introduction of OpenGL by SGI in 1992 paved the way for standard hardware-independent 3D programming interfaces.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] However, by the mid and late 90s, professional hardware was being slowly eclipsed by consumer products which offered similar or even better performance, especially in regards to texture mapping, at a lower cost and on platforms familiar to end users.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In 1991, S3 Graphics introduced the *S3 86C911*, which its designers named after the Porsche 911 as an indication of the performance increase it promised.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The 86C911 spawned a variety of imitators: by 1995, all major PC graphics chip makers had added 2D acceleration support to their chips.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Fixed-function *Windows accelerators* surpassed expensive general-purpose graphics coprocessors in Windows performance, and such coprocessors faded from the PC market.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In the early- and mid-1990s, real-time 3D graphics became increasingly common in arcade, computer, and console games, which led to increasing public demand for hardware-accelerated 3D graphics.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Early examples of mass-market 3D graphics hardware can be found in arcade system boards such as the Sega Model 1, Namco System 22, and Sega Model 2, and the fifth-generation video game consoles such as the Saturn, PlayStation, and Nintendo 64.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Arcade systems such as the Sega Model 2 and SGI Onyx-based Namco Magic Edge Hornet Simulator in 1993 were capable of hardware T&L (transform, clipping, and lighting) years before appearing in consumer graphics cards.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In 1994, Sony used the term GPU (with the meaning graphics processing unit) in reference to the PlayStation console's Toshiba-designed Sony GPU.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Another early example is the Super FX chip, a RISC-based on-cartridge graphics chip used in some SNES games, notably *Doom* and *Star Fox*.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Some systems used DSPs to accelerate transformations.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Fujitsu, which worked on the Sega Model 2 arcade system, began working on integrating T&L into a single LSI solution for use in home computers in 1995; the Fujitsu Pinolite, the first 3D geometry processor for personal computers, announced in 1997.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The first hardware T&L GPU on home video game consoles was the Nintendo 64's Reality Coprocessor, released in 1996.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In 1997, Mitsubishi released the 3Dpro/2MP, a GPU capable of transformation and lighting, for workstations and Windows NT desktops; ATi used it for its FireGL 4000 graphics card, released in 1997.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The term "GPU" was coined by Sony in reference to the 32-bit Sony GPU (designed by Toshiba) in the PlayStation video game console, released in 1994.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Pixel shading is often used for bump mapping, which adds texture to make an object look shiny, dull, rough, or even round or extruded.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] With the introduction of the Nvidia GeForce 8 series and new generic stream processing units, GPUs became more generalized computing devices.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] GPGPUs were the precursors to what is now called a compute shader (e.g.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] CUDA, OpenCL, DirectCompute) and actually abused the hardware to a degree by treating the data passed to algorithms as texture maps and executing algorithms by drawing a triangle or quad with an appropriate pixel shader.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] This entails some overheads since units like the scan converter are involved where they are not needed (nor are triangle manipulations even a concern—except to invoke the pixel shader).
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's CUDA platform, first introduced in 2007, was the earliest widely adopted programming model for GPU computing.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] OpenCL is an open standard defined by the Khronos Group that allows for the development of code for both GPUs and CPUs with an emphasis on portability.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] OpenCL solutions are supported by Intel, AMD, Nvidia, and ARM, and according to a report in 2011 by Evans Data, OpenCL had become the second most popular HPC tool.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In 2010, Nvidia partnered with Audi to power their cars' dashboards, using the Tegra GPU to provide increased functionality to cars' navigation and entertainment systems.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Advances in GPU technology in cars helped advance self-driving technology.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] AMD's Radeon HD 6000 series cards were released in 2010, and in 2011 AMD released its 6000M Series discrete GPUs for mobile devices.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The Kepler line of graphics cards by Nvidia were released in 2012 and were used in the Nvidia 600 and 700 series cards.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] A feature in this GPU microarchitecture included GPU boost, a technology that adjusts the clock-speed of a video card to increase or decrease according to its power draw.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Kepler also introduced NVENC video encoding acceleration technology.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The PS4 and Xbox One were released in 2013; they both used GPUs based on AMD's Radeon HD 7850 and 7790.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's Kepler line of GPUs was followed by the Maxwell line, manufactured on the same process.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's 28 nm chips were manufactured by TSMC in Taiwan using the 28 nm process.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Compared to the 40 nm technology from the past, this manufacturing process allowed a 20 percent boost in performance while drawing less power.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Virtual reality headsets have high system requirements; manufacturers recommended the GTX 970 and the R9 290X or better at the time of their release.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Cards based on the Pascal microarchitecture were released in 2016.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The GeForce 10 series of cards are of this generation of graphics cards.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] They are made using the 16 nm manufacturing process which improves upon previous microarchitectures.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In 2018, Nvidia launched the RTX 20 series GPUs that added ray tracing cores to GPUs, allowing real time ray tracing to be performant on mass market hardware.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Polaris 11 and Polaris 10 GPUs from AMD are fabricated by a 14 nm process.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Their release resulted in a substantial increase in the performance per watt of AMD video cards.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] AMD also released the Vega GPU series for the high end market as a competitor to Nvidia's high end Pascal cards, also featuring HBM2 like the Titan V.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In 2019, AMD released the successor to their Graphics Core Next (GCN) microarchitecture/instruction set.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Dubbed RDNA, the first product featuring it was the Radeon RX 5000 series of video cards.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The company announced that the successor to the RDNA microarchitecture would be incremental (a "refresh").
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] AMD unveiled the Radeon RX 6000 series, its RDNA 2 graphics cards with support for hardware-accelerated ray tracing.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The product series, launched in late 2020, consisted of the RX 6800, RX 6800 XT, and RX 6900 XT.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The RX 6700 XT, which is based on Navi 22, was launched in early 2021.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The PlayStation 5 and Xbox Series X and Series S were released in 2020; they both use GPUs based on the RDNA 2 microarchitecture with incremental improvements and different GPU configurations in each system's implementation.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In the 2020s, GPUs have been increasingly used for calculations involving embarrassingly parallel problems, such as training of neural networks on enormous datasets that are needed for artificial intelligence large language models.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Specialized processing cores on most modern GPUs that are dedicated to deep learning provide significant FLOPS performance increases, using 4×4 matrix multiplication and division.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Early implementations, such as Nvidia's Volta microarchitecture, released in 2017, saw results of up to 128 TFLOPS in some applications.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Since then, AI acceleration cores have been a widely adopted feature in consumer and workstation microarchitectures starting with Nvidia's Turing microarchitecture in 2018, named Tensor cores.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] AMD originally implemented their equivalent "Matrix" Cores for consumers in their RDNA 3 architecture - however RDNA 4's Matrix Cores were the first to introduce FP8 acceleration - which is required to run the full FSR Redstone feature set such as Machine Learning Upscaling and Frame Generation.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] However, community made hacks on both Linux and Windows have allowed RDNA 2, 3, and competitor GPUs to run a weaker version of FSR 4 known as FSR 4 INT8.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] The PlayStation 5 Pro, launched in 2024, has customized Machine Learning cores - which focus solely on INT8 acceleration - based on RDNA 4's for PlayStation Spectral Super Resolution to enhance framerates and image quality.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Intel has implemented their equivalent "XMX" Cores in all of their Arc GPUs, starting with the Alchemist microarchitecture.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] This is used for XeSS (Xe Super Sampling), XeFG (Xe Frame Generation), and more.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] Ray tracing has also been incredibly prevalent in the 2020s with some games, such as DOOM: The Dark Ages, requiring a hardware ray tracing capable GPU to even start.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] While it does lead to worse performance and less overall accessibility, id software claimed this saved several man hours and shrinked the game by over 100 gigabytes due to the game being entirely built around ray tracing .
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] In 2013, 438.3 million GPUs were shipped globally and the forecast for 2014 was 414.2 million.
[src:ultralight-ui/graphics-processing-unit] However, by the third quarter of 2022, shipments of PC GPUs totaled around 75.5 million units, down 19% year-over-year.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Web browsers receive HTML documents from a web server or from local storage and render the documents into multimedia web pages.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] HTML describes the structure of a web page semantically and originally included cues for its appearance.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] HTML elements are the building blocks of HTML pages.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] With HTML constructs, images and other objects such as interactive forms may be embedded into the rendered page.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] HTML provides a means to create structured documents by denoting structural semantics for text such as headings, paragraphs, lists, links, quotes, and other items.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] HTML elements are delineated by *tags*, written using angle brackets.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Tags such as `<img>` and `<input>` directly introduce content into the page.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Other tags such as `<p>` and its corresponding closing tag `</p>` surround and provide information about document text and may include sub-element tags.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Browsers do not display the HTML tags, but use them to interpret the content of the page.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] HTML can embed programs written in a scripting language such as JavaScript, which affects the behavior and content of web pages.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The inclusion of CSS defines the look and layout of content.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), former maintainer of the HTML and current maintainer of the CSS standards, has encouraged the use of CSS over explicit presentational HTML since 1997.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] A form of HTML, known as HTML5, is used to display video and audio, primarily using the `<canvas>` element, together with JavaScript.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In 1980, the physicist Tim Berners-Lee, a contractor at CERN, proposed and prototyped ENQUIRE, a system for CERN researchers to use and share documents.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In 1989, Berners-Lee wrote a memo proposing an Internet-based hypertext system.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Berners-Lee specified HTML and wrote the browser and server software in late 1990.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] That year, Berners-Lee and CERN data systems engineer Robert Cailliau collaborated on a joint request for funding, but the project was not formally adopted by CERN.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In his personal notes of 1990, Berners-Lee listed "some of the many areas in which hypertext is used"; an encyclopedia is the first entry.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The first publicly available description of HTML was a document called "HTML Tags", first mentioned on the Internet by Tim Berners-Lee in late 1991.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] It describes 18 elements comprising the initial, relatively simple design of HTML.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Except for the hyperlink tag, these were strongly influenced by CERN SGML, an in-house Standard Generalized Markup Language (SGML)-based documentation format at CERN.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Eleven of these elements still exist in HTML 4.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] HTML is a markup language that web browsers use to interpret and compose text, images, and other material into visible or audible web pages.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Default characteristics for every item of HTML markup are defined in the browser, and these characteristics can be altered or enhanced by the web page designer's additional use of CSS.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] These formatting commands were derived from the commands used by typesetters to manually format documents.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] However, the SGML concept of generalized markup is based on elements (nested annotated ranges with attributes) rather than merely print effects, with separate structure and markup.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] HTML has been progressively moved in this direction with CSS.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Berners-Lee considered HTML to be an application of SGML.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The draft expired after six months, but was notable for its acknowledgment of the NCSA Mosaic browser's custom tag for embedding in-line images, reflecting the IETF's philosophy of basing standards on successful prototypes.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Similarly, Dave Raggett's competing Internet Draft, "HTML+ (Hypertext Markup Format)", from late 1993, suggested standardizing already-implemented features like tables and fill-out forms.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] After the HTML and HTML+ drafts expired in early 1994, the IETF created an HTML Working Group.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In 1995, this working group completed "HTML 2.0", the first HTML specification intended to be treated as a standard against which future implementations should be based.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Further development under the auspices of the IETF was stalled by competing interests.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Since 1996, the HTML specifications have been maintained, with input from commercial software vendors, by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In 2000, HTML became an international standard (ISO/IEC 15445:2000).
[src:ultralight-ui/html] HTML 4.01 was published in late 1999, with further errata published through 2001.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In 2004, development began on HTML5 in the Web Hypertext Application Technology Working Group (WHATWG), which became a joint deliverable with the W3C in 2008, and was completed and standardized on 28 October 2014.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] It was the first version developed and standardized exclusively by the W3C, as the IETF had closed its HTML Working Group on 12 September 1996.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] were omitted due to a mutual agreement between the two companies.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] HTML 4 is an SGML application conforming to ISO 8879 – SGML.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] was reissued with minor edits without incrementing the version number.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] HTML", based on HTML 4.01 Strict) was published as an ISO/IEC international standard.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] (ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1, Subcommittee 34 – Document description and processing languages).
[src:ultralight-ui/html] After HTML 4.01, there were no new versions of HTML for many years, as the development of the parallel, XML-based language XHTML occupied the W3C's HTML Working Group.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] an informal CERN document listing 18 HTML tags, was first mentioned in public.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] IIIR Working Group as an Internet Draft (a rough proposal for a standard).
[src:ultralight-ui/html] HTML+ was published by the IETF as an Internet Draft and was a competing proposal to the Hypertext Markup Language draft.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] It included many of the capabilities that were in Raggett's HTML+ proposal, such as support for tables, text flow around figures, and the display of complex mathematical formulas.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] but HTML 3.0 did not succeed for several reasons.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The draft was considered very large at 150 pages and the pace of browser development, as well as the number of interested parties, had outstripped the resources of the IETF.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Browser vendors, including Microsoft and Netscape at the time, chose to implement different subsets of HTML 3's draft features as well as to introduce their own extensions to it.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] has abandoned any attempt to be an SGML application and has explicitly defined its own "html" serialization, in addition to an alternative XML-based XHTML5 serialization.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] On 14 February 2011, the W3C extended the charter of its HTML Working Group with clear milestones for HTML5.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In May 2011, the working group advanced HTML5 to "Last Call", an invitation to communities inside and outside W3C to confirm the technical soundness of the specification.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The W3C developed a comprehensive test suite to achieve broad interoperability for the full specification by 2014, which was the target date for recommendation.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In January 2011, the WHATWG renamed its "HTML5" living standard to "HTML".
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The W3C nevertheless continued its project to release HTML5.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] W3C will continue the HTML5 specification work, focusing on a single definitive standard, which is considered a "snapshot" by WHATWG.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The WHATWG organization will continue its work with HTML5 as a "Living Standard".
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The concept of a living standard is that it is never complete and is always being updated and improved.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] New features can be added but functionality will not be removed.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In December 2012, W3C designated HTML5 as a Candidate Recommendation.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] is "two 100% complete and fully interoperable implementations".
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In September 2014, W3C moved HTML5 to Proposed Recommendation.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] meaning the specification process is complete.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] XHTML is a separate language that began as a reformulation of HTML 4.01 using XML 1.0.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] It is now referred to as *the XML syntax for HTML* and is no longer being developed as a separate standard.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] On 28 May 2019, the W3C announced that WHATWG would be the sole publisher of the HTML and DOM standards.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The W3C and WHATWG had been publishing competing standards since 2012.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] While the W3C standard was identical to the WHATWG in 2007 the standards have since progressively diverged due to different design decisions.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The WHATWG "Living Standard" had been the *de facto* web standard for some time.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The W3C periodically reviews and publishes snapshots of the WHATWG HTML specification as W3C Recommendations.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] HTML markup consists of several key components, including those called *tags* (and their *attributes*), character-based *data types*, *character references* and *entity references*.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] HTML tags most commonly come in pairs like `<h1>` and `</h1>`, although some represent *empty elements* and so are unpaired, for example `<img>`.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The first tag in such a pair is the *start tag*, and the second is the *end tag* (they are also called *opening tags* and *closing tags*).
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Another important component is the HTML *document type declaration*, which triggers standards mode rendering.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The text between `<html>` and `</html>` describes the web page, and the text between `<body>` and `</body>` is the visible page content.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The markup text `<title>This is a title</title>` defines the browser page title shown on browser tabs and window titles and the tag `<div>` defines a division of the page used for easy styling.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Between `<head>` and `</head>`, a `<meta>` element can be used to define webpage metadata.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The Document Type Declaration `<!DOCTYPE html>` is for HTML5.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] If a declaration is not included, various browsers will revert to "quirks mode" for rendering.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] HTML documents imply a structure of nested HTML elements.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] These are indicated in the document by HTML *tags*, enclosed in angle brackets.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In the simple, general case, the extent of an element is indicated by a pair of tags: a "start tag" `<p>` and "end tag" `</p>`.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The text content of the element, if any, is placed between these tags.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Tags may also enclose further tag markup between the start and end, including a mixture of tags and text.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] This indicates further (nested) elements, as children of the parent element.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The start tag may also include the element's *attributes* within the tag.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Some elements, such as the line break `<br>` do not permit *any* embedded content, either text or further tags.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] These require only a single empty tag (akin to a start tag) and do not use an end tag.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Many tags, particularly the closing end tag for the very commonly used paragraph element `<p>`, are optional.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] An HTML browser or other agent can infer the closure for the end of an element from the context and the structural rules defined by the HTML standard.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] These rules are complex and not widely understood by most HTML authors.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The general form of an HTML element is therefore: `<tag attribute1="value1" attribute2="value2">''content''</tag>`.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Some HTML elements are defined as *empty elements* and take the form `<tag attribute1="value1" attribute2="value2">`.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Empty elements may enclose no content, for instance, the `<br>` tag or the inline `<img>` tag.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The name of an HTML element is the name used in the tags.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The end tag's name is preceded by a slash character `/`.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] If a tag has no content, an end tag is not allowed.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] If attributes are not mentioned, default values are used in each case.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Header of the HTML document: `<head>...</head>`.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] CSS can substantially change the rendering.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The difference between `<br>` and `<p>` is that `<br>` breaks a line without altering the semantic structure of the page, whereas `<p>` sections the page into paragraphs.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The element `<br>` is an *empty element* in that, although it may have attributes, it can take no content and it must not have an end tag.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The `href` attribute holds the URL address of the link.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Comments can help in the understanding of the markup and do not display in the webpage.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Most of the attributes of an element are name–value pairs, separated by `=` and written within the start tag of an element after the element's name.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The value may be enclosed in single or double quotes, although values consisting of certain characters can be left unquoted in HTML (but not XHTML).
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Leaving attribute values unquoted is considered unsafe.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In contrast with name-value pair attributes, there are some attributes that affect the element simply by their presence in the start tag of the element, like the `ismap` attribute for the `img` element.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Most elements take the language-related attribute `dir` to specify text direction, such as with "rtl" for right-to-left text in, for example, Arabic, Persian or Hebrew.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] As of version 4.0, HTML defines a set of 252 character entity references and a set of 1,114,050 numeric character references, both of which allow individual characters to be written via simple markup, rather than literally.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] A literal character and its markup counterpart are considered equivalent and are rendered identically.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The ability to "escape" characters in this way allows for the characters `<` and `&` (when written as `&lt;` and `&amp;`, respectively) to be interpreted as character data, rather than markup.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] For example, a literal `<` normally indicates the start of a tag, and `&` normally indicates the start of a character entity reference or numeric character reference; writing it as `&amp;` or `&#x26;` or `&#38;` allows `&` to be included in the content of an element or in the value of an attribute.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The double-quote character (`"`), when not used to quote an attribute value, must also be escaped as `&quot;` or `&#x22;` or `&#34;` when it appears within the attribute value itself.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Equivalently, the single-quote character (`'`), when not used to quote an attribute value, must also be escaped as `&#x27;` or `&#39;` (or as `&apos;` in HTML5 or XHTML documents) when it appears within the attribute value itself.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] If document authors overlook the need to escape such characters, some browsers can be very forgiving and try to use context to guess their intent.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The result is still invalid markup, which makes the document less accessible to other browsers and to other user agents that may try to parse the document for search and indexing purposes for example.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Escaping also allows for characters that are not easily typed, or that are not available in the document's character encoding, to be represented within the element and attribute content.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Unicode character encodings such as UTF-8 are compatible with all modern browsers and allow direct access to almost all the characters of the world's writing systems.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] HTML defines several data types for element content, such as script data and stylesheet data, and a plethora of types for attribute values, including IDs, names, URIs, numbers, units of length, languages, media descriptors, colors, character encodings, dates and times, and so on.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] All of these data types are specializations of character data.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] HTML documents are required to start with a document type declaration (informally, a "doctype").
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In browsers, the doctype helps to define the rendering mode—particularly whether to use quirks mode.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The original purpose of the doctype was to enable the parsing and validation of HTML documents by SGML tools based on the document type definition (DTD).
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The DTD to which the DOCTYPE refers contains a machine-readable grammar specifying the permitted and prohibited content for a document conforming to such a DTD.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Browsers, on the other hand, do not implement HTML as an application of SGML and as consequence do not read the DTD.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] This declaration references the DTD for the "strict" version of HTML 4.01.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] SGML-based validators read the DTD in order to properly parse the document and to perform validation.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In modern browsers, a valid doctype activates standards mode as opposed to quirks mode.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In addition, HTML 4.01 provides Transitional and Frameset DTDs, as explained below.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The transitional type is the most inclusive, incorporating current tags as well as older or "deprecated" tags, with the Strict DTD excluding deprecated tags.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The frameset has all tags necessary to make frames on a page along with the tags included in transitional type.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Semantic HTML is a way of writing HTML that emphasizes the meaning of the encoded information over its presentation (look).
[src:ultralight-ui/html] HTML has included semantic markup from its inception, but has also included presentational markup, such as `<font>`, `<i>`, and `<center>` tags.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] There are also the semantically neutral div and span tags.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Since the late 1990s, when Cascading Style Sheets were beginning to work in most browsers, web authors have been encouraged to avoid the use of presentational HTML markup with a view to the separation of content and presentation.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In a 2001 discussion of the Semantic Web, Tim Berners-Lee and others gave examples of ways in which intelligent software "agents" may one day automatically crawl the web and find, filter, and correlate previously unrelated, published facts for the benefit of human users.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Such agents are not commonplace even now, but some of the ideas of Web 2.0, mashups and price comparison websites may be coming close.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] An important type of web agent that does crawl and read web pages automatically, without prior knowledge of what it might find, is the web crawler or search-engine spider.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] These software agents are dependent on the semantic clarity of web pages they find as they use various techniques and algorithms to read and index millions of web pages a day and provide web users with search facilities without which the World Wide Web's usefulness would be greatly reduced.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Presentational markup tags are deprecated in current HTML and XHTML recommendations.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The majority of presentational features from previous versions of HTML are no longer allowed as they lead to poorer accessibility, higher cost of site maintenance, and larger document sizes.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Good semantic HTML also improves the accessibility of web documents (see also Web Content Accessibility Guidelines).
[src:ultralight-ui/html] For example, when a screen reader or audio browser can correctly ascertain the structure of a document, it will not waste the visually impaired user's time by reading out repeated or irrelevant information when it has been marked up correctly.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] HTML documents can be delivered by the same means as any other computer file.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] However, they are most often delivered either by HTTP from a web server or by email.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The World Wide Web is composed primarily of HTML documents transmitted from web servers to web browsers using the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
[src:ultralight-ui/html] However, HTTP is used to serve images, sound, and other content, in addition to HTML.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] To allow the web browser to know how to handle each document it receives, other information is transmitted along with the document.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] This meta data usually includes the MIME type (e.g., text/html or application/xhtml+xml) and the character encoding (see Character encodings in HTML).
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In modern browsers, the MIME type that is sent with the HTML document may affect how the document is initially interpreted.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] A document sent with the XHTML MIME type is expected to be well-formed XML; syntax errors may cause the browser to fail to render it.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The same document sent with the HTML MIME type might be displayed successfully since some browsers are more lenient with HTML.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The W3C recommendations state that XHTML 1.0 documents that follow guidelines set forth in the recommendation's Appendix C may be labeled with either MIME Type.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] XHTML 1.1 also states that XHTML 1.1 documents should be labeled with either MIME type.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Most graphical email clients allow the use of a subset of HTML (often ill-defined) to provide formatting and semantic markup not available with plain text.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] This may include typographic information like colored headings, emphasized and quoted text, inline images and diagrams.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Many such clients include both a GUI editor for composing HTML e-mail messages and a rendering engine for displaying them.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Use of HTML in e-mail is criticized by some because of compatibility issues, because it can help disguise phishing attacks, because of accessibility issues for blind or visually impaired people, because it can confuse spam filters and because the message size is larger than plain text.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The most common filename extension for files containing HTML is .html.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] A common abbreviation of this is .htm, which originated because some operating systems limit file extensions to three letters.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] An HTML Application (HTA; file extension .hta) is a Microsoft Windows application that uses HTML and Dynamic HTML in a browser to provide the application's graphical interface.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] A regular HTML file is confined to the security model of the web browser's security, communicating only to web servers and manipulating only web page objects and site cookies.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] An HTA runs as a fully trusted application and therefore has more privileges, like creation/editing/removal of files and Windows Registry entries.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Because they operate outside the browser's security model, HTAs cannot be executed via HTTP, but must be downloaded (just like an EXE file) and executed from local file system.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Since its inception, HTML and its associated protocols gained acceptance relatively quickly.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] However, no clear standards existed in the early years of the language.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Though its creators originally conceived of HTML as a semantic language devoid of presentation details, practical uses pushed many presentational elements and attributes into the language, driven largely by the various browser vendors.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The latest standards surrounding HTML reflect efforts to overcome the sometimes chaotic development of the language and to create a rational foundation for building both meaningful and well-presented documents.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] To return HTML to its role as a semantic language, the W3C has developed style languages such as CSS and XSL to shoulder the burden of presentation.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In conjunction, the HTML specification has slowly reined in the presentational elements.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] There are two axes differentiating various variations of HTML as currently specified: SGML-based HTML versus XML-based HTML (referred to as XHTML) on one axis, and strict versus transitional (loose) versus frameset on the other axis.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] One difference in the latest HTML specifications lies in the distinction between the SGML-based specification and the XML-based specification.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The XML-based specification is usually called XHTML to distinguish it clearly from the more traditional definition.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] However, the root element name continues to be "html" even in the XHTML-specified HTML.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The W3C intended XHTML 1.0 to be identical to HTML 4.01 except where limitations of XML over the more complex SGML require workarounds.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Because XHTML and HTML are closely related, they are sometimes documented in parallel.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In such circumstances, some authors conflate the two names as (X)HTML or X(HTML).
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Like HTML 4.01, XHTML 1.0 has three sub-specifications: strict, transitional, and frameset.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Aside from the different opening declarations for a document, the differences between an HTML 4.01 and XHTML 1.0 document—in each of the corresponding DTDs—are largely syntactic.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The underlying syntax of HTML allows many shortcuts that XHTML does not, such as elements with optional opening or closing tags, and even empty elements which must not have an end tag.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] By contrast, XHTML requires all elements to have an opening tag and a closing tag.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] XHTML, however, also introduces a new shortcut: an XHTML tag may be opened and closed within the same tag, by including a slash before the end of the tag like this: `<br/>`.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The introduction of this shorthand, which is not used in the SGML declaration for HTML 4.01, may confuse earlier software unfamiliar with this new convention.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] A fix for this is remove the slash preceding the closing angle bracket, as such: `<br>`.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] To understand the subtle differences between HTML and XHTML, consider the transformation of a valid and well-formed XHTML 1.0 document that adheres to Appendix C (see below) into a valid HTML 4.01 document.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Change the document type declaration from XHTML 1.0 to HTML 4.01.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Ensure that the document's MIME type is set to `text/html`.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] For both HTML and XHTML, this comes from the HTTP `Content-Type` header sent by the server.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Change the XML empty-element syntax to an HTML style empty element (`<br/>` to `<br>`).
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Those are the main changes necessary to translate a document from XHTML 1.0 to HTML 4.01.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] To translate from HTML to XHTML would also require the addition of any omitted opening or closing tags.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Whether coding in HTML or XHTML it may just be best to always include the optional tags within an HTML document rather than remembering which tags can be omitted.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] A well-formed XHTML document adheres to all the syntax requirements of XML.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] A valid document adheres to the content specification for XHTML, which describes the document structure.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The W3C recommends several conventions to ensure an easy migration between HTML and XHTML.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] By carefully following the W3C's compatibility guidelines, a user agent should be able to interpret the document equally as HTML or XHTML.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] For documents that are XHTML 1.0 and have been made compatible in this way, the W3C permits them to be served either as HTML (with a `text/html` MIME type), or as XHTML (with an `application/xhtml+xml` or `application/xml` MIME type).
[src:ultralight-ui/html] When delivered as XHTML, browsers should use an XML parser, which adheres strictly to the XML specifications for parsing the document's contents.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] HTML 4 defined three different versions of the language: Strict, Transitional (once called Loose), and Frameset.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The Strict version is intended for new documents and is considered best practice, while the Transitional and Frameset versions were developed to make it easier to transition documents that conformed to older HTML specifications or did not conform to any specification to a version of HTML 4.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The Transitional and Frameset versions allow for presentational markup, which is omitted in the Strict version.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Instead, cascading style sheets are encouraged to improve the presentation of HTML documents.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Because XHTML 1 only defines an XML syntax for the language defined by HTML 4, the same differences apply to XHTML 1 as well.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The Frameset version includes everything in the Transitional version, as well as the `frameset` element (used instead of `body`) and the `frame` element.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In addition to the above transitional differences, the frameset specifications (whether XHTML 1.0 or HTML 4.01) specify a different content model, with `frameset` replacing `body`, that contains either `frame` elements, or optionally `noframes` with a `body`.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] As this list demonstrates, the loose versions of the specification are maintained for legacy support.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] However, contrary to popular misconceptions, the move to XHTML does not imply a removal of this legacy support.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Rather the X in XML stands for extensible and the W3C is modularizing the entire specification and opens it up to independent extensions.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The primary achievement in the move from XHTML 1.0 to XHTML 1.1 is the modularization of the entire specification.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The strict version of HTML is deployed in XHTML 1.1 through a set of modular extensions to the base XHTML 1.1 specification.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Likewise, someone looking for the loose (transitional) or frameset specifications will find similar extended XHTML 1.1 support (much of it is contained in the legacy or frame modules).
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Modularization also allows for separate features to develop on their own timetable.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] So for example, XHTML 1.1 will allow quicker migration to emerging XML standards such as MathML (a presentational and semantic math language based on XML) and XForms—a new highly advanced web-form technology to replace the existing HTML forms.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] In summary, the HTML 4 specification primarily reined in all the various HTML implementations into a single clearly written specification based on SGML.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] XHTML 1.0, ported this specification, as is, to the new XML-defined specification.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] Next, XHTML 1.1 takes advantage of the extensible nature of XML and modularizes the whole specification.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] XHTML 2.0 was intended to be the first step in adding new features to the specification in a standards-body-based approach.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The HTML Living Standard, which is developed by WHATWG, is the official version, while W3C HTML5 is no longer separate from WHATWG.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] WYSIWYG editors (*what you see is what you get*), are HTML editors in which the user lays out everything as it is to appear in the HTML document using a graphical user interface (GUI), such as Microsoft FrontPage, often similar to word processors.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The editor renders the document rather than showing the code, so authors do not require extensive knowledge of HTML.
[src:ultralight-ui/html] The WYSIWYG editing model has been criticized, primarily because of the low quality of the generated code; there are various developers advocating a change to the WYSIWYM model (*what you see is what you mean*).
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] A **software framework** is software that provides reusable, generic functionality which developers can extend or customize to create complete solutions.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] It offers an abstraction layer over lower-level code and infrastructure, allowing developers to focus on implementing business logic rather than building common functionality from scratch.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] Generally, a framework is intended to enhance productivity by allowing developers to focus on satisfying business requirements rather than reimplementing generic functionality.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] Frameworks often include support programs, compilers, software development kits, code libraries, toolsets, and APIs that integrate various components within a larger software platform or environment.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] Unlike a library, where user code controls the program's control flow, a framework implements inversion of control by dictating the overall structure and calling user code at predefined extension points (e.g., through template methods or hooks).
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] Frameworks also provide default behaviours that work out-of-the-box, structured mechanisms for extensibility, and a fixed core that accepts extensions (e.g., plugins or subclasses) without direct modification.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] A framework differs from an application that can be extended—such as a web browser via an extension or a video game via a mod—in that it is intentionally incomplete scaffolding designed to be completed through its extension points while following specific architectural patterns.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] For example, a team using a web framework to develop a banking website can focus on writing banking business logic rather than handling low-level details like web request processing or state management.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] According to Pree, software frameworks consist of *frozen spots* and *hot spots*.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] *Frozen spots* define the overall architecture of a software system, that is to say its basic components and the relationships between them.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] These remain unchanged (frozen) in any instantiation of the application framework.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] *Hot spots* represent the parts where the programmers using the framework add their own code to add the functionality specific to their own project.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] The necessary functionality can be implemented by using the Template Method Pattern in which the *frozen spots* are known as invariant methods and the *hot spots* are known as variant or hook methods.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] The invariant methods in the superclass provide default behaviour while the hook methods in each subclass provide custom behaviour.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] When developing a concrete software system with a software framework, developers utilize the hot spots according to the specific needs and requirements of the system.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] Software frameworks rely on the Hollywood Principle: "Don't call us, we'll call you." This means that the user-defined classes (for example, new subclasses) receive messages from the predefined framework classes.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] Developers usually handle this by implementing superclass abstract methods.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] One potential downside of using a framework is that it adds to the size of a program, a phenomenon termed code bloat.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] This can be exacerbated by using multiple, sometimes competing, frameworks in the same codebase.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] Learning how to use a framework can be substantial.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] The intended efficiencies of using the framework may be outweighed by the cost to learn it, especially for a framework that is new to the development staff.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] However, once a framework is learned, development team speed may increase for future work.
[src:ultralight-ui/software-framework] Some claim that the most effective frameworks evolve from re-factoring an existing solution, such as a generic one-size-fits-all framework developed by third parties for general purposes, rather than from green-field development.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] During the late 1970s and early 1980s, mostly stimulated by the hang gliding movement, many people sought affordable powered flight.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] As a result, many aviation authorities set up definitions of lightweight, slow-flying aeroplanes that could be subject to minimum regulations.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] The resulting aeroplanes are commonly called "ultralight aircraft" or "Microlights", although the weight and speed limits differ from country to country.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] In Europe, the sporting (FAI) definition limits the maximum stalling speed to 65 km/h (35 kn) and the maximum take-off weight to 450 kg (992 lb), or 472.5 kg (1,042 lb) if a ballistic parachute is installed.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] The definition means that the aircraft has a slow landing speed and short landing roll in the event of an engine failure.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] In most affluent countries, Microlights or ultralight aircraft now account for a significant percentage of the global civilian-owned aircraft.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] For instance, in Canada in February 2018, the ultralight aircraft fleet made up to 20.4% of the total civilian aircraft registered.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] In other countries that do not register ultralight aircraft, like in the United States, it is unknown what proportion of the total fleet they make up.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] In countries where there is no specific extra regulation, ultralights are considered regular aircraft and subject to certification requirements for both aircraft and pilot.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] In Australia, ultralight aircraft and their pilots can either be registered with the Hang Gliding Federation of Australia (HGFA) or Recreational Aviation Australia (RA Aus).
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] In all cases, except for privately built single seat ultralight aeroplanes, microlight aircraft or trikes are regulated by the Civil Aviation Regulations.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] Pilots of a powered, fixed wing aircraft or paramotors do not need a licence, provided its weight with a full fuel tank is not more than 75 kg (165 lb), but they must obey the rules of the air.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] For heavier microlights the current UK regulations are similar to the European ones, but helicopters and gyroplanes are not included.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] Other than the very earliest aircraft, all two-seat UK microlights (and until 2007 all single-seaters) have been required to meet an airworthiness standard; BCAR Section S.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] In 2007, Single Seat DeRegulated (SSDR), a sub-category of single seat aircraft was introduced, allowing owners more freedom for modification and experiments.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] By 2017 the airworthiness of all single seat microlights became solely the responsibility of the user, but pilots must hold a microlight licence; currently NPPL(M) (National Private Pilots Licence).
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] Ultralights in New Zealand are subject to NZCAA General Aviation regulations with microlight specific variations as described in Part 103 and AC103-1.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] The United States FAA's definition of an ultralight is significantly different from that in most other countries and can lead to some confusion when discussing the topic.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] The governing regulation in the United States is FAR 103 Ultralight Vehicles.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] In 2004, the FAA introduced the "Light-sport aircraft" category, which resembles some other countries' microlight categories.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] Ultralight aviation is represented by the United States Ultralight Association (USUA), which acts as the US aeroclub representative to the Fédération Aéronautique Internationale.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] Advancements in batteries, motors, and motor controllers has led to some practical production electric propulsion systems for some ultralight applications.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] In many ways, ultralights are a good application for electric power as some models are capable of flying with low power, which allows longer duration flights on battery power.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] In 2007, the first pioneering company in this field, the Electric Aircraft Corporation, began offering engine kits to convert ultralight weight shift trikes to electric power.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] The 18 hp motor weighs 26 lb (12 kg) and an efficiency of 90% is claimed by designer Randall Fishman.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] The battery consists of a lithium-polymer battery pack of 5.6 kWh which provides 1.5 hours of flying in the trike application.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] The company claimed a flight recharge cost of 60 cents in 2007.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] A significant obstacle to the adoption of electric propulsion for ultralights in the U.S. is the weight of the battery, which is considered part of the empty weight of the aircraft despite efforts to have it considered as fuel.
[src:ultralight-ui/ultralight] As the specific energy of batteries improves, lighter batteries can be used.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] WebKit started as a fork of the KHTML and KJS libraries from KDE, and has since been further developed by KDE contributors, Apple, Google, Nokia, Bitstream, BlackBerry, Sony, Igalia, and others.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] WebKit supports macOS, Windows, Linux, and various other Unix-like operating systems.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] On April 3, 2013, Google announced that it had forked WebCore, a component of WebKit, to be used in future versions of Google Chrome under the name Blink.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Since version 15 in May 2013, Opera web browser has dropped its own Presto layout engine in favor of WebKit as implemented by Google in the Chromium project.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Its JavaScript engine, JavaScriptCore, also powers the Bun server-side JS runtime, as opposed to V8 used by Node.js, Deno, and Blink.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] WebKit's C++ application programming interface (API) provides a set of classes to display Web content in windows, and implements browser features such as following links when clicked by the user, managing a back-forward list, and managing a history of pages recently visited.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] WebKit is open source and available under the BSD 2-Clause license with the exception of the WebCore and JavaScriptCore components, which are available under the GNU Lesser General Public License.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] As of March 7, 2013, WebKit is a trademark of Apple, registered with the United States Patent and Trademark Office.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] The code that would become WebKit began in 1998 as the *KDE HTML* (KHTML) layout engine and *KDE JavaScript* (KJS) engine.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] The WebKit project was started within Apple by Lisa Melton on June 25, 2001, as a fork of KHTML and KJS.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Melton explained in an e-mail to KDE developers that KHTML and KJS allowed easier development than other available technologies by virtue of being small (fewer than 140,000 lines of code), cleanly designed, and standards-compliant.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] KHTML and KJS were ported to macOS with the help of an adapter library and renamed to WebCore and JavaScriptCore.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] JavaScriptCore was announced in an e-mail to a KDE mailing list in June 2002, alongside the first release of Apple's changes.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] The exchange of code between WebCore and KHTML became increasingly difficult as the code bases diverged, because both projects used different coding approaches and had different approaches to code sharing.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] At one point KHTML developers said they were unlikely to accept Apple's changes and claimed the relationship between the two groups was a "bitter failure".
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] They claimed Apple submitted their changes in large patches containing multiple changes with inadequate documentation, often in relation to future additions to the codebase.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Thus, these patches were difficult for the KDE developers to integrate back into KHTML.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Also, Apple had demanded that developers sign non-disclosure agreements before looking at Apple's source code, and even then, they were unable to access Apple's bug database.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] During the publicized "divorce" period, KDE developer Kurt Pfeifle (*pipitas*) posted an article claiming KHTML developers had managed to backport many (but not all) Safari improvements from WebCore to KHTML, and they always appreciated the improvements coming from Apple and still do so.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] The article also noted that Apple had begun contacting KHTML developers to discuss improving the relationship and future cooperation.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] In fact, the KDE project was able to incorporate some of these changes to improve KHTML's rendering speed and add features, including compliance with the Acid2 rendering test.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Following the appearance of a story of the fork in the news, Apple released the source code of the WebKit fork in a public revision-control repository.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] The WebKit team also reversed many Apple-specific changes in the original WebKit codebase and implemented platform-specific abstraction layers, making it significantly easier to commit the core rendering code to other platforms.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] In July 2007, *Ars Technica* reported that the KDE team would move from KHTML to WebKit.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Instead, after several years of integration, KDE Development Platform version 4.5.0 was released in August 2010 with support for both WebKit and KHTML, and development of KHTML continued until 2016 before it was officially discontinued in 2023.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] On June 7, 2005, Safari developer Dave Hyatt announced on his weblog that Apple was open-sourcing WebKit (formerly, only WebCore and JavaScriptCore were open source) and opening up access to WebKit's revision control tree and the issue tracker.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] In mid-December 2005, support for Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG) was merged into the standard build.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] WebKit's JavaScriptCore and WebCore components are available under the GNU Lesser General Public License, while the rest of WebKit is available under the BSD 2-Clause license.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Beginning in early 2007, the development team began to implement Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) extensions, including animation, transitions and both 2D and 3D transforms; such extensions were released as working drafts to the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) in 2009 for standardization.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] In November 2007, the project announced that it had added support for media features of the HTML5 draft specification, allowing embedded video to be natively rendered and script-controlled in WebKit.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] On June 2, 2008, the WebKit project announced that they had rewritten JavaScriptCore as "SquirrelFish", a bytecode interpreter.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] The project evolved into SquirrelFish Extreme (abbreviated SFX), announced on September 18, 2008, which compiles JavaScript into native machine code, eliminating the need for a bytecode interpreter and thus speeding up JavaScript execution.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Initially, the only supported processor architecture for SFX was the x86, but at the end of January 2009, SFX was enabled for macOS on x86-64 as it passes all tests on that platform.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] On April 8, 2010, a project named WebKit2 was announced to redesign WebKit.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Its goal was to abstract the components that provide page layout and rendering cleanly from their surrounding interface or application shell, creating a situation where "web content (JavaScript, HTML, layout, etc) lives in a separate process from the application UI".
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] This abstraction was intended to make reuse in WebKit2 simpler than in WebKit.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] WebKit2 had "an incompatible API change from the original WebKit", which motivated its name change.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] The WebKit2 targets were set to Linux, macOS, Windows, GTK, and MeeGo-Harmattan.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Safari for macOS switched to the new API with version 5.1.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Safari for iOS switched to WebKit2 with iOS 8.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] The original WebKit API has been renamed WebKitLegacy API.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] WebKit2 API has been renamed just plain WebKit API.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] WebKit is used as the rendering engine within Safari and was used by Google's Chrome web browser on Windows, macOS, and Android (before version 4.4 KitKat).
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Chrome used only WebCore, and included its own JavaScript engine named V8 and a multiprocess system.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Chrome for iOS continues to use WebKit because Apple requires that web browsers on that platform must do so.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Other applications on macOS and iOS make use of WebKit, such as Apple's e-mail client Mail, App Store, and the 2008 version of Microsoft's Entourage personal information manager, both of which make use of WebKit to render HTML content.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] New web browsers have been built around WebKit such as the S60 browser on Symbian mobile phones, BlackBerry Browser (ver 6.0+), Midori, Chrome browser, the Android Web browsers before version 4.4 KitKat, and the browser used in PlayStation 3 system software from version 4.10.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] KDE's Rekonq web browser and Plasma Workspaces also use it as the native web rendering engine.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] WebKit has been adopted as the rendering engine in OmniWeb, iCab, Web (formerly named Epiphany), and Sleipnir, replacing their original rendering engines.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] GNOME's Web supported both Gecko and WebKit for some time.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Still, the team decided that Gecko's release cycle and future development plans would make it too cumbersome to continue supporting it. webOS uses WebKit as the basis of its application runtime.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] WebKit is used to render HTML and run JavaScript in the Adobe Integrated Runtime application platform.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] In Adobe Creative Suite CS5, WebKit is used to render some parts of the user interface.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] By the first half of 2010, an analyst estimated that 350 million mobile handsets had shipped with a WebKit-based browser.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] By mid-April 2015, WebKit browser market share was 50.3%.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] The week after Hyatt announced WebKit's open sourcing, Nokia announced that it had ported WebKit to Symbian and was developing a WebKit-based browser for mobile phones running S60.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Named Web Browser for S60, it was used on Nokia, Samsung, LG, and other Symbian S60 mobile phones.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Apple has also ported WebKit to iOS for the iPhone, iPod Touch, and iPad, where it is used to render content in the device's web browser and e-mail software.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] The Android mobile phone platform used WebKit (and later versions its Blink fork) as the basis of its web browser and the Palm Pre, announced January 2009, has an interface based on WebKit.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] The Amazon Kindle 3 includes an experimental WebKit based browser.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] In June 2007, Apple announced that WebKit had been ported to Microsoft Windows as part of Safari.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Although the company silently discontinued Safari for Windows, WebKit's ports to Microsoft's operating system are still actively maintained.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] The Windows port uses Apple's proprietary libraries to function and is used for iCloud and iTunes for Windows, whereas the "WinCairo" port is a fully open-source and redistributable port.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] WebKit has also been ported to several toolkits that support multiple platforms, such as the GTK toolkit for Linux, under the name *WebKitGTK* which is used by Eolie, GNOME Web, Adobe Integrated Runtime, Enlightenment Foundation Libraries (EFL), and the Clutter toolkit.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Qt Software included a WebKit port in the Qt 4.4 release as a module called QtWebKit (since superseded by Qt WebEngine, which uses Blink instead).
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] The Iris Browser on Qt also used WebKit.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] The Enlightenment Foundation Libraries (EFL) port – EWebKit – was developed (by Samsung and ProFusion) focusing the embedded and mobile systems, for use as stand alone browser, widgets-gadgets, rich text viewer and composer.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] The Clutter port is developed by Collabora and sponsored by Robert Bosch GmbH.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] There was also a project synchronized with WebKit (sponsored by Pleyo) called *Origyn Web Browser*, which provided a meta-port to an abstract platform to make porting to embedded or lightweight systems quicker and easier.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] This port is used for embedded devices such as set-top boxes and PMP and it has been ported into AmigaOS, AROS, and MorphOS.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] MorphOS version 1.7 is the first version of Origyn Web Browser (OWB) supporting HTML5 media tags.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] On April 3, 2013, Google announced that it would produce a fork of WebKit's WebCore component, to be named Blink.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Chrome's developers decided to fork WebCore to allow greater freedom in implementing its features in the browser without causing conflicts upstream, and to simplify its codebase by removing code for WebCore components unused by Chrome.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] In relation to Opera Software's announcement earlier in the year that it would switch to WebKit by means of the Chromium codebase, it was confirmed that the Opera web browser would also switch to Blink.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Following the announcement, WebKit developers began discussions on removing Chrome-specific code from the engine to streamline its codebase.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] WebKit no longer has any Chrome specific code (e.g., buildsystem, V8 JavaScript engine hooks, platform code, etc.).
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] WebCore is a layout, rendering, and Document Object Model (DOM) library for HTML and Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG), developed by the WebKit project.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Its full source code is licensed under the GNU Lesser General Public License (LGPL).
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] WebKit passes the Acid2 and Acid3 tests, with pixel-perfect rendering and no timing or smoothness issues on reference hardware.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] JavaScriptCore is a framework that provides a JavaScript engine for WebKit implementations, and provides this type of scripting in other contexts within macOS.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] JavaScriptCore is originally derived from KDE's JavaScript library KJS (which is part of the KDE project) and the PCRE regular expression library.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] Since forking from KJS and PCRE, JavaScriptCore has added many new features and greatly improved performance.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] On June 2, 2008, the WebKit project announced they rewrote JavaScriptCore as "SquirrelFish", a register-based bytecode interpreter replacing the original AST-walking interpreter.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] The project later evolved into SquirrelFish Extreme (abbreviated SFX, marketed as Nitro), announced on September 18, 2008, further speeding up JavaScript execution by introducing Just-in-time compilation.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] An optimizing just-in-time (JIT) compiler named *FTL* was announced on May 13, 2014.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] It uses LLVM to generate optimized machine code.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] "FTL" stands for "Fourth-Tier-LLVM", and unofficially for faster-than-light, alluding to its speed.
[src:ultralight-ui/webkit] As of February 15, 2016, the backend of FTL JIT is replaced by "Bare Bones Backend" (or B3 for short).
